This is the rate at which the Central Bank giants advances to commercial banks for their temporary liquidity purposes. However, since August, 1977 each bank, depending on selected asset items was allocated a certain quota of such borrowings at the Bank Rate. Borrowings in excess of this quota were subjected to a penal rate of 15 per cent per annum. In September, 1979, a graduated scale of penal rates ranging between 15 to 25 per cent was introduced. It

; was further revised upward to a range between 20 to 30 per cent effective from April, 1980. From 17th, August 1981, the Bank rate was raised to 14 per cent. While the penal rates ranged between 21 to 30 per cent. With effect from 30th March, 1983, the Bank rate brought down to 13 per cent and the penal rate was fixed at a flat rate of 20 per cent. With effect from 23rd November 1983, the practice of granting penal rate advances to commercial banks was discontinued. With effect from 30th December 1985 the Central Bank reduced the Bank rate to 11 per cent and further to 10 per cent with effect from 7th August, 1987.
